ing is the positive likelihood ratio for this diagnostic test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["2.25","7.2","4.5","9.0","0.125"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe positive likelihood ratio (LR+) is calculated by dividing sensitivity by (1 - specificity). In this case:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELR+ = 0.90 / (1 - 0.80) = 0.90 / 0.20 = \u003Cstrong\u003E4.5\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive likelihood ratio of 4.5 means that a positive test result is 4.5 times more likely to occur in someone with the disease than in someone without the disease. Values between 2-5 indicate fair diagnostic test performance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Positive likelihood ratio equals sensitivity divided by (1 - specificity).","A positive likelihood ratio indicates how much more likely a positive test result is in people with the disease compared to those without it.","Higher positive likelihood ratios indicate better diagnostic test performance, with values \u003E10 considered excellent."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56166"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17481"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56166"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:25:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:27:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10171"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70701"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic 